Anonymous Sun 14 Feb 2021 23:19:23 No.36335091 Report

Yeah, that's where second person's strengths shine imo
>>36334841
If you use second person for a story where the character isn't supposed to be a self insert, it can be immersion breaking when that character makes a decision that the reader wouldn't. But the longer a work is, the more it relies on the characters to keep the reader invested. You may find difficulty keeping the story interesting if the POV character is a blank slate for the reader to insert themselves in, which is the approach a lot of people take. It can be done, no doubt, especially if you already have a cast of characters that are more fleshed out but it's certainly difficult and perhaps not optimal.

Anonymous Sun 14 Feb 2021 23:46:38 No.36335761 Report
Quoted By: >>36336359
>>36335091
>where the character isn't supposed to be a self insert...
And there's the Catch 22
A poor use of second person relies on the fact that there's no drama in the choices. Even the hard ones are obvious. The reader becomes passive.
A better use is to make it feel more like reading a kid's CYOA book. There are no good choices, and you have obvious doubts reflected back at you. Still, it's passive but not as much as before.
The best use of second person, and where it goes literary, is to start by hooking the passive reader. Then you slowly get them to agree with things they'd never do. Could be one wham sentence at the end. But each choice allows the reader to vote on disagreeing with you.

Beating the passivity out of second person is not what I want to do with my time. I can write more, and more clearly, in first or third person.
